1. e4 {In August 1891, at "Cafe' de la Regence" in Paris, a young man sat down
for the first time in front of a chessboard. His name was David Janowsky,
about 23 years old, polish origin. For all the chessplayers who used to attend
that famous place serious troubles began!} 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. c3
{The Scotch Gambit} 4... Bc5 {Accepting the Gambit 4... dxc3, after 5. Bc4 Nf6
6. Nxc3 Bb4 7. O-O O-O Black keeps his extra pawn in a comfortable position.}
5. Bc4 Nf6 {entering a variation of the Giuoco Piano.} 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Bd2
Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. O-O (10. Qb3 {is believed to the best reply}
10... Nce7 ({inferior for Black would be} 10... Na5 {
for the possible continuation} 11. Qa4+ c6 12. Bxd5 Qxd5 13. O-O O-O 14. Rac1
Qb5 15. Qa3 b6 16. Qc3 Bd7 17. Ne5 Rad8 18. Ndf3 {necessary in order to
protect the Pd4, so that, by threatening b2-b4, White can win the Pc6.} {If}
18... f6 {then} 19. Nxd7 Rxd7 20. b4)) 10... O-O 11. Re1 Nf4 12. Ne4 Ne7 {
A useless Knight maneuver.} ({
The presence of a Black Knight in f4 would have allowed} 12... Be6 {
and if White would have decided to trade the Bishops} 13. Bxe6 fxe6 {after} 14.
Nc5 Qd5 15. Nxb7 Rab8 16. Nc5 Rxb2 {the position is clearly better for Black.})
13. Qd2 Neg6 14. h3 Nd5 {
Unclear. Again, a better choice would have been 14...Be6 or 14...c6.} 15. Rac1
c6 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17. Rc5 {Now Goetz has to face the dilemma: accept or not
accept the Pa2? A greedy attitude would allow a White kingside attack which is
not a joke.} 17... Qxa2 {So Black decided for the capture. One cannot say it
was a mistake. A post-mortem analysis proved that a carefull defense would
have allowed to resist the attack, remaining with a extra pawn.} 18. Rh5 f6 {
The best reply.  On the other hand 18... h6 could not be played because of 19.
Rxh6 gxh6 20.Qxh6} 19. Nd6 b6 {Probably to prevent Rh5-a5. So the position is
much more complex than it appears.} ({
Then, perhaps, it would have helped better for the purpose the reply} 19... Rd8
20. Ra5 ({But White could have had protected the Knight with} 20. Qb4 {and if}
20... a5 ({But is also possible} 20... Nf4 21. Ra5 Nd5 {(!)} 22. Qd2 Qb3 {
and White has nothing left.}) 21. Qc5 Nf4 22. Rh4 Ne6 23. Qh5 {
give it in exchange for the victory} 23... Rxd6 24. Qxh7+ Kf7 25. Rg4 Bd7 26.
Nh4 Rg8 27. Nf5 {and Black is lost.}) 20... Qb3 21. Re3 Qb6 22. Nc4 Qc7 {
and the White attack vanishes.}) 20. Qc2 {Very good! A very strong move,
attacks the c6 Pawn and, by blocking the g6 Knight takes the necessary time to
bring the second Rook on the seventh rank. Now the attack will continue in a
coherent and sharp way.} 20... Bd7 21. Re7 Rad8 22. Nh4 Be8 23. Nhf5 Bf7 24. d5
{Closing the diagonal a2-g8. Terrific!} 24... Nf4 ({
Goetz could not take the Pawn} 24... cxd5 25. Nxf7 Rxf7 26. Rxf7 Kxf7 27. Qc7+
{and mate in seven follows.}) 25. Nxf7 Rxf7 {
If 25... Nxh5 26. N5h6+ and mate in two.} 26. Rxf7 Nxh5 27. Nh6+ Kh8 28. dxc6
Qd5 29. c7 Rc8 30. Rf8+ Rxf8 31. c8=Q 1-0

