1. Nf3 {In 1892, at "Cafe' de la Regence" a tournament was organized among the
strongest players who were present in Paris at that time. The prize was 500
francs. Janowsky and Sittenfeld were those who play against each other in the
final match. The result, in favour of our hero, was +7 -5 =5. The game which
is now presented here won the beauty prize of 30 francs.} 1... Nc6 2. d4 d5 {
Janowsky would not have disliked (in case of 3.c4) the Chigorin Defense even
if such a defense was already at that time partially condemned by the theory.}
3. e3 Bg4 4. Be2 e6 5. c3 {A bit too shy. Wasn't it better to castle and then
attack the center with c2-c4?} 5... Nf6 6. Qb3 Rb8 7. Nbd2 Bd6 8. Nf1 {
Unclear...} 8... Ne4 {...and Black profits from it at once.} 9. Ng3 O-O 10. Bd3
{The first mistake. It was better to play immediatly 10. Ng1 to force the
Bishop exchange and to open the kingside to the air, since it is beginning to
"smell sweat".} 10... f5 {Very good!} 11. a3 (11. c4 {(?)} 11... Bb4+ 12. Bd2
Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Nxd2 14. Kxd2 f4 {(-/+)}) 11... Kh8 12. Bd2 b5 {So, even a
ble breaking attempt with c3-c4 is prevented. But that's not all. This move
and the following ones, as we shall see, are part of a deep strategical plan
to further reduce the space available for the opponent. A real attempt to
strangle him!} 13. Qc2 a5 14. b4 Qf6 15. Bc1 Qh6 {Exclamation mark!} 16. Nf1 {
Forced. 16...Nxg3 was threatened.} 16... Qh5 17. Ng1 {No! Too passive! Also,
let's say it: it is humiliating too! It seems that White is taken by terror.
The threat f2-f3 is unreal and allows Black....} 17... e5 {Wonderful!} 18. f3 {
(?) Sittenfeld could not resist to such temptation.} (18. Bxe4 fxe4 {(-/+)}) (
18. Ne2 exd4 19. cxd4 {and the Pb4 is lost.} (19. exd4 {
and the "f" Pawn seems to be instoppable.})) 18... Qh4+ 19. g3 Nxg3 20. Nxg3 e4
{Down! In the mouth of the enemy!} 21. f4 {To defend against Bd6xg3+.} 21...
exd3 22. Qxd3 g5 {Breathless! (A Bout de souffle!)} 23. Qf1 {(?)} ({
Relatively better was} 23. N1e2 Bxe2 24. Kxe2) 23... gxf4 24. exf4 Rfe8+ 25.
Kd2 axb4 {Now the King is out of is lair and Black goes to the queenside.} 26.
axb4 Qe7 27. Kc2 Bxb4 {It's time!} 28. cxb4 Qxb4 29. Qd3 Ra8 {(!)} (29... Nxd4+
{(?)} 30. Qxd4+ Qxd4 31. Bb2) 30. Rxa8 ({If} 30. Rb1 {then} 30... Nxd4+ 31.
Qxd4+ Qxd4 32. Bb2 Ra2) 30... Rxa8 31. N1e2 Ra2+ 32. Kd1 Nxd4 33. Qe3 Rxe2 34.
Nxe2 Bxe2+ 0-1

