1. e4 {Hasting. August,5 - September,2 1895. A prestigious tournament,
organized in order to compare the playing strength of the top chess champions
at that time. Chigorin, Lasker, Tarrasch, Steinitz, Schlechter and other 17
players were participating. All of them were very strong players. Among them
Janowsky and a new talented american player Harry Nelson Pillsbury, who won
the tournament with 16.5 points out of 21. Janowsky, for various reasons not
at his best playing strength, was however successfull in defending his
reputation he had gained in Paris.} 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5.
O-O Nge7 {Steinitz, always faithful to his favoured defense, this time has
improved it with the move a7-a6.} 6. Bb3 {An interesting Bishop move.} 6... Na5
7. d4 {What is that? Some strange impulse or a new idea? Janowsky seems ready
to give his lightsquare Bishop for the sake of attack. Is that too much?
Pillsbury, categorically, commented: "Such a move should cost the game to
White."} 7... exd4 8. Nxd4 c5 9. Nf5 Nxf5 {(?) Pillsbury again: "Probably this
exchange is a real mistake. A deadly mistake, I would say. After 9...Bxf5 10.
exf5 White would have lost a piece without compensation." Is it possible that
both Janowsky and Steinitz overlooked the simple continuation suggested by
Pillsbury? Uhmm ... hard to believe.  And in fact, the moves 9... Bxf5 10.
exf5 c4 11. Nc3 (!)  cxb3 12. axb3  followed  by Rf1-e1 and Nc3-d5 (or Nc3-e4)
should make worry the Black's conductor. Let's say that his position, with the
King in the middle of the chessboard, half-undressed, seems at least unclear.
Open windows and doors create air currents which are dangerous for healt. If,
for instance, 12...Nxf5 then 13.Qd5 would win the piece back with advantage.
If then White would play at once 11.Re1, Black, before taking the Bishop,
should scratch his head and think about it one, two, ten times before doing it.
Maybe Pillsbury, with the presumption tha can be told from his words, did "pee
counter wind", to use an italian expression.} 10. exf5 Nxb3 {
Of course now it is too late to play 10...c4 because of 11.Qe2+.} ({
Here Schallop advise} 10... Bxf5 {making the remark that after} 11. Re1+ Be7
12. Bxf7+ {(?!)} (12. Bg5 f6 (12... Nc6 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Qd5) 13. Bf4 ({
Adventurous and a bit unclear would have been} 13. Nc3 fxg5 14. Nd5 Nc6 15.
Qh5+ Kd7 16. Rad1) 13... Nxb3 14. axb3 {(!)} 14... d5 15. Nc3 d4 16. Nb5 {(!)}
16... O-O (16... axb5 17. Rxa8 Qxa8 18. Bd6) 17. Nc7 Rc8 18. Qf3 {
with more the adequate compensation for the pawn.}) 12... Kxf7 13. Qd5+ Kg6 14.
Re3 {and Black can control the attack with 14...Bh4 15.Rf3 Qd7. But Janowsky,
as we had already seen, instead of playing the unclear 12.Bxf7+, could have
played 12.Bg5 (!) which looks much stronger. Let's look up few lines, examine
one more this variation and the wealt of possibilities we shall see will let
us understand once again the reason of our love for the fantastic game of
chess.}) 11. Re1+ {Maybe Steinitz has been too quick in willing to eliminate
the dangerous lightsquare Bishop. Maybe, probably, surely indeed, Janowsky
will show us that his opponent "fell out the frying pan into the fire"!} 11...
Be7 12. f6 {(!) Have you seen?} 12... gxf6 ({
Of course, the Rook can not be taken} 12... Nxa1 13. Rxe7+ Kf8 14. Qh5 Be6 15.
Bh6 {(!)}) 13. axb3 d5 {Perhaps, as a last attempt to stop the imminent
catastrophe, Steinitz could have tried 13...Be6 14.Qh5 Qd7.} 14. Qh5 Qd6 {
It is a bit difficult to think that Black could have escaped by sacrificing a
Rook for a minor piece: 14...0-0 15.Bh6. And what if Steinitz wanted to save
this too playing 15...Re8?  Then after 16.Nc3 he could have left the table and
go sell nuts and beans at the Astor movie theather in his hometown.} 15. Nc3
Be6 16. Nb5 {(!!) How does it begin the Fifth Simphony of Beethoven? Da-da-da..
.dawn! The "theme of destiny"!} 16... Qc6 ({Once again Schallop shows us that} 
16... Qb8 {would have not prevented White from making irreparable damages with
the continuation} 17. Nc7+ ({Again better} 17. Nd4 cxd4 (17... Bd7 18. Nf5 Bxf5
19. Qxf5 Qd6 20. Bf4 Qc6 21. Re2 {and then Ra1-e1.}) 18. Rxe6 Qc7 19. Bh6 O-O-O
20. Qxf7) ({but, maybe, it was enough the simple} 17. Bf4 Qxf4 18. Rxe6) 17...
Qxc7 18. Rxe6 {However, even if Janowsky would have chosen this variation as
Schallop advised (and we have seen that there were at least two more
variations which could have been better) with 18...Qd7 19.Re1 0-0-0 20.Qxf7
Rde8, Black can "only" choose a slower death.  Certainly some masochism would
have been necessary. Apparently Steinitz decided that he would not let the
"sadistic" Janowsky to enjoy any longer.}) 17. Rxe6 Qxb5 18. Bh6 Kd8 19. Qxf7
Re8 20. Rae1 {Is it clear that White is aiming the "e7" and "f6" squares? No?
Ok, let's go on.} 20... Qd7 21. Bg7 {Now it should be clear!} 21... Rc8 22.
Bxf6 Bxf6 23. Qxf6+ {
The shortest way. Now one could announce mate in seven (Fritz says).} (23.
Rxe8+ Kc7 24. Rxc8+ {and then 25.Qxf6}) 23... Kc7 24. Qe5+ {Steinitz resigns.}
1-0

