{This elegant little game deserves to be better known.Played in a tournament
where Botvinnik was at the top of his form, its merits have been overshadowed
by a half dozen other masterpieces that he produced in the course of the
competition.The clever way in which Botvinnik gains control of the center is
by itself a delight, two amusing queen moves being reminiscent of a similar
subtle strategy employed by Nimzowitsch in his famous encounter with Johner at
Dresden in 1926. Those two moves alone are worth the price of admission.} 1. e4
e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {The Nimzowitsch variation, wherein White drives a wedge
into the opponent's position. 3...} 3... c5 {
The proper response, an attack on the center.} 4. Nf3 {Nimzowitsch advocated
over-protection of the wedge (the king pawn) with pieces, even if it meant
loss of the queen pawn. He reccomended 4.Qg4, though, as he said, it was a
move that would appeal only to the few; it is not everybody'fancis to give up
a pawn, and afterwards-not to play for an attack. 4...} 4... Nc6 5. Bd3 {
A teporary loan of a pawn in the spirit of the gambit. 5...} 5... cxd4 6. O-O
Bc5 7. a3 {This seems slow, for gambit play. White should develop (and
over-protect) by 7.Bf4. 7...} 7... Nge7 8. Nbd2 {This is routine play, whereas
proper timing required 8.Bf4. If the 8...Ng6 in reply, the Bishop can settle
down nively at g3. 8...} 8... Ng6 {
Initiates an attack on the all-important king pawn.} 9. Nb3 Bb6 10. Re1 Bd7 11.
g3 {Preparation for an attack by 12.h4 and 13.h5, but the king knight loses a
pawn support - a circumstance thet will not escape Botvinnik's notice.} ({
Less chances were offered by} 11. Bxg6 hxg6 {
(open the rook file) and Black wins a pawn.} 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qh4) 11...
f6 {A third attack on the king pawn. White must now either give up the center
by 12.exf6, or part with his precious king bishop.} 12. Bxg6+ hxg6 {
The open rook file is bound to benefit Black.} 13. Qd3 ({
White can win back his pawn, only to run into other troubles, thus:} 13. Nbxd4
Nxd4 14. Nxd4 fxe5 15. Rxe5 Qf6 16. f4 g5 17. c3 gxf4 18. Bxf4 Bc7 {
and White's position will quickly crumble.}) 13... Kf7 $1 14. h4 {A necessary
provision for 15.Bf4, which if playedat once meets 14...g5 in reply.
Botvinnik's next move is a profound one. It deserves a an exclamation point or
two. 14...} 14... Qg8 $3 {This beautiful queen maneuver crosses up White's
plan to regain his pawn without losing hold of the center. White intended to
protect his king pawn by 15.Bf4 (now that...g6-g5 is prevented) and then
capture the queen pawn at his leisure.} 15. Bd2 ({White abandons} 15. Bf4 {
, realizing that he is in for trouble after a few moves, the continuation
being 15...} 15... Qh7 16. Nbxd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 g5 {and the threats of 18...
gxf4 or 18...Qxd3 followed by 19...Bxd4 force 18.Qxh7 Rxh7 19.Be3, when 19...
fxe5 wins a pawn, and in short order the game itself.}) 15... Qh7 $1 16. Bb4 {
So the Bishop tries another tack! It is headed either for Bd6, to bolster the
king pawn, or for Bc5, in an attempt to eliminate one of Black's potentially
dangerous bishop. 16...} 16... g5 {Now we begin to see the depth pf
Botvinnik's strategy. He will force the removal of White's annoying king pawn,
and then build up a strong pawn center of his own, even though it costs him a
pawn.} 17. Qxh7 Rxh7 18. exf6 {There was no way to maintain the center.} ({If} 
18. hxg5 fxe5 19. Nxe5+ Nxe5 20. Rxe5 Bc7 21. Re2 e5 {
and threats (one such being 22...Bg4 followed by 23...Bf3)begin to spring up.})
18... gxf6 19. hxg5 e5 $1 20. gxf6 Kxf6 {As a result of his thoughtful
planning, Botvinnik has a powerful center, two bishops eagerly waiting in the
background, and open files at the disposal of his rooks. In contrast, his
opponent's pieces have no opportunity of obtaining a foothold in the center.}
21. Bd6 Re8 22. Nh4 Rg8 $1 {Threatens to remove the knight.} 23. Kh2 ({
The poor creature may not even return, as after} 23. Nf3 {there comes 23...}
23... d3 $1 {and the threat of 24...Rxg3+ wins quickly.}) 23... Bf5 24. Re2 d3
25. Rd2 ({Or} 25. cxd3 Bxd3 26. Rd2 Bc4 27. Nc1 Nd4 {
(threatens the rook by 28...Nf3+)} 28. Rd1 (28. Kh3 Bf1+) 28... Nf3+ 29. Kh3
Bxf2 {and White can stop struggling.}) 25... dxc2 26. f4 Be3 27. Bxe5+ {
Moving the rook to e2 instead, loses like a shot by 27...Bxf4! 27...} 27...
Nxe5 28. fxe5+ Ke7 29. Rf1 ({On} 29. Re2 Bf4 {admits of no reply.}) 29... c1=Q
$1 {This breaks down all resistance. An impressive performance by Botvinnik.} (
29... c1=Q 30. Nxc1 (30. Rxc1 Rxh4+ 31. gxh4 Bf4+ 32. Kh1 Be4+ {
and Black wins both rooks.}) 30... Bxd2 31. Rxf5 Bxc1 {wins a rook.}) 0-1

