{The first part of the following game (up to 17th move) consists mainly in
consolidating monoeuvres on either side. We then see how a localised
contest-conducted on what appears to be a sector of secondary
importance-unexpectedly becomes the principal theme of the game, thanks in the
main to Black's beautiful pawn sacrifice (19...c3) an the coordination of his
minor pieces.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Bc5 6. O-O d6 7.
d4 exd4 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. d5 {The chief protagonist of this move (instead of 9.
Bb2 or 9.Nc3) was Anderssen.  9...} 9... Na5 {This manoeuvre, if effected
without delay, does not represent loss of time, as White's Bishop must react
sooner or later, and Black can find the necessary breathing space to
consolidate his position.} 10. Bb2 Ne7 {By this move Black shows that he has
no fear of 11.Bxg7, because of 11...Rg8; and Black would have the initiative.}
({Attending to his development} 10... Nxc4 11. Qa4+ Bd7 12. Qxc4 {
would only help White to a sound disposition of his forces.}) 11. Bd3 O-O 12.
Nc3 Ng6 13. Ne2 {After the violent initial skirmishes, the play is now
characterised by subtle manoeuvres. This "positional" aspect of the Evans
Gambit shows its wide resources.  13...} 13... c5 {
Following up the advantage which he has acquired on the Queen side.} 14. Qd2 f6
{Restricting the range of adverse QB on the long diagonal.} (14... c4 {
would be useless against} 15. Bc2) 15. Kh1 Bd7 ({
An alternative line of play on Black's queen side would be} 15... Bc7 16. Rac1
Rb8 17. Ng3 b5 18. Nf5 c4 19. Be2 {etc., with chances on both sides.}) 16. Rac1
a6 17. Ne1 ({He continues his preparations for the advance of his f2 pawn, but
more in keeping with the requirements of the situation would have been} 17. Ng3
Bb5 18. Nf5 c4 19. Be2 {etc.}) 17... Bb5 18. f4 c4 19. Bb1 c3 {A very deep
sacrifice of a pawn. It not only vacates a square in order to let in an
important unit (the Na5), but it also entangles the enemy forces, with the
additional hope of turning the open "c" file to account.} 20. Rxc3 (20. Nxc3
Bxf1) (20. Qxc3 Bxe2) (20. Bxc3 Nc4 {followed by Ne3, winning the excange.})
20... Nc4 21. Qc1 Rc8 {This reinforces the outpost position taken up by the
QKt, and threatens, "inter alia" 22...Ba5, 23.Rc2 Nd2 etc.} 22. Bd3 Be3 {
A decisive irruption.} 23. Qc2 Nd2 {The complement of Black's preceding move.
Black's control of the weak squares, which he ultimately turns into material
advantage, is very remarkable.} 24. Rg1 Rxc3 25. Qxc3 Qb6 26. Bc1 Bxg1 27. Nxg1
Bxd3 28. Nxd3 Nxe4 {(White resign)} 29. Qb2 (29. Qc4 Re8) (29. Qc2 Qd4 {
threatening 30...Qxd3 31.QxQ Nf2#} 30. Nh3 Re8 31. Bb2 Qxd3 32. Qxd3 Nf2+ 33.
Nxf2 Re1+ {with mate to follow.}) 29... Qxb2 30. Bxb2 Nxf4 31. Nxf4 Nf2# {
From "500 Master Games of Chess" Dover Publications - New York 1975} 0-1

