have now 16...Kxf8, then 17.Qxe7+ Kg8 18.Qe6+ Kf8 19.Be7+ then he could not
avoid a checkmate. Therefore ... ha, ha, ... he stopped the clock as a sign of
his surrender. And he was unfortunately also ethically compelled to shake my
hand, to me, his violator! Ha, ha, ha, ha....!"Terrible! PS. In the truth this
game is not the same of this tournament, but only one very similar, to avoid
to recognize this "poor fellow". I have instead reported the Sokolsky-Kofman
game, played in Kiev 1948. To the more curious can I only say that our man is
